In this case, you will need to ensure that the applicationSet includes at least one resourceType before you can successfully use the /asset/api/v1/resources API. Here’s how you can proceed step-by-step:

Step-by-Step Guide

1. Create or Update the ApplicationSet with a ResourceType

First, use the POST /asset/api/v1/applicationsets endpoint to add a resourceType to your applicationSet. Make sure to include the applicationSetResourceTypes with at least one defined resourceType.

Here’s an example of the JSON payload to use:

{
  "applicationSet": "PPM",
  "applicationName": "PPM",
  "cmdbApplicationId": "e8767abe4f348700c5ce44f18110c764",
  "cmdbApplicationDescription": "PPM",
  "applicationSetResourceTypes": [
    {
      "resourceType": "PPM Administration",
      "attributes": [
        {
          "attribute": "Access Level",
          "dataType": "String"
        }
      ],
      "actions": [
        {
          "action": "View",
          "description": "View access",
          "responseValue": "read",
          "actionType": "read"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}

Ensure that the resource type ("PPM Administration") and other details match what you intend to use for the /asset/api/v1/resources API. This ensures that the applicationSet has a resourceType available.

2. Verify the ApplicationSet and ResourceType

After creating or updating the applicationSet, use the GET /asset/api/v1/applicationsets endpoint to verify that the resourceType has been added successfully. Look for the resourceType under the applicationSetResourceTypes field.

3. Add a Resource to the ApplicationSet Using the /asset/api/v1/resources API

Now that the resourceType is defined, you can use the /asset/api/v1/resources endpoint to add a specific resource under the existing resourceType.

Here's an example of the JSON payload you might use:

{
  "applicationSet": "PPM",
  "cmdbApplicationId": "e8767abe4f348700c5ce44f18110c764",
  "resourceType": "PPM Administration"
}

applicationSet: Use the name of the applicationSet you created (e.g., "PPM").

cmdbApplicationId: This should match the ID used when creating the applicationSet.

resourceType: This should match the resourceType you specified earlier (e.g., "PPM Administration").


In Postman, select the POST method, enter the URL for /asset/api/v1/resources, and include this payload in the Body with JSON (application/json) format.

4. Troubleshooting Common Issues

If you get an error regarding resourceType, ensure that it is exactly as you defined it in applicationSetResourceTypes.

Make sure that the applicationSet and cmdbApplicationId are accurate and match what you’ve already created.

Double-check for any JSON formatting issues (like missing or extra commas) that could cause parsing errors.


By following these steps, you should be able to define a resourceType within your applicationSet and then add specific resources under that resourceType using the /asset/api/v1/resources API.


